                            <h1>Renee Zhao, Age 14</h1>
                            <p>Chinatown means a lot to me, and I don’t even know how to start. I guess I should start with my history. I was in Chinatown when I was little. I guess this is why Chinatown means so much to me--I was already involved with it when I was young. Unfortunately, I moved out and I currently reside fifteen minutes away.</p>

                            <p>At first glance, Chinatown might just seem like a place for tourists; you see all of these shops and restaurants just scattered around. But that is not the case. Chinatown is home to many families and is a second home to many others. I consider Chinatown as my second home because I am always there. I go to school there and can be seen eating out with my family or friends there on a daily basis.</p>

                            <p>Chinatown is a place where you can do anything. As I mentioned before, you can find many shops and restaurants there. Chinatown has many markets that sell food that can not commonly found in other places  Food such as bitter melon, lotus root, and salted plum are common items sold there. There are restaurants for all different types of Chinese food, Japanese, Korean, Mandarin, Thai, Asian fusions, and Vietnamese. Or you can grab a bao or an egg tart for a quick snack. Chinatown is also expanding. You can now even find a French bakery there.</p>

                            <p>Aside from shops and bakeries, you can also find resources there. There is a library, a post office, a medical center, many orthodontic centers, and salons. It is a community. The library is built just last year. You can find people reading books, getting homework help, doing school projects, and just hanging out there. The library has two floors full of computers and books. There is both Chinese and English books and that is what makes the Chinatown library different from the other libraries. There are two different languages.</p>

                            <p>Chinatown is always bustling, day and time. There are people who walk to and from work, students who go to school, and people who have lunch across the street during lunch break. Breakfast and brunch can be purchased from the bakery. Lunch can be eaten anywhere; the convenience of Chinatown makes it simple. Dinner is usually eaten at the restaurant. Sometimes, restaurants become so crowded that they can only wait in line. There are many restaurants in Chinatown, so people don't crowd around a restaurant, which is a good thing.</p>

                            <p>The busiest time of Chinatown in the year is the Chinese New Year. Chinese New Year has a parade every year. This is the moment of gratitude, family and friends. People can see groceries and festive sweets for kids. Chinatown is a place for everyone. We always see people stopping at the store or restaurant to greet each other. This is because Chinatown is considered to be the home of most of us and it will be our home. Many visitors to Chinatown are immediately attracted to their beauty and friendliness, including myself. This is why Chinatown is of great significance to me.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="zh_HANS">
                            <h1>Renee Zhao, 14岁</h1>
